    {
      "content": "An error message dialog box will appear advising you that all the references to the template should be removed.",
      "pos": [
        5797,
        5908
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can delete all the references to the template by accessing the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Volume Containers<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> page and modifying the volume containers that use this template so that they use another template or use a custom or unlimited bandwidth setting.",
      "pos": [
        5910,
        6144
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When all the references have been removed, you can delete the template.",
      "pos": [
        6145,
        6216
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Use a default bandwidth template",
      "pos": [
        6221,
        6253
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A default bandwidth template is provided and is used by volume containers by default to enforce bandwidth controls when accessing the cloud.",
      "pos": [
        6255,
        6395
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The default template also serves as a ready reference for users who create their own templates.",
      "pos": [
        6396,
        6491
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The details of this default template are:",
      "pos": [
        6492,
        6533
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        6537,
        6577
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Name<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> – Unlimited nights and weekends"
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Schedule<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> – A single schedule from Monday to Friday that applies a bandwidth rate of 1 Mbps between 8 AM and 5 PM device time.",
      "pos": [
        6581,
        6710
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The bandwidth is set to Unlimited for the remainder of the week.",
      "pos": [
        6711,
        6775
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The default template can be edited.",
      "pos": [
        6777,
        6812
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The usage of this template (including edited versions) is tracked.",
      "pos": [
        6813,
        6879
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Create an all-day bandwidth template that starts at a specified time",
      "pos": [
        6884,
        6952
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Follow this procedure to create a schedule that starts at a specified time and runs all day.",
      "pos": [
        6954,
        7046
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In the example, the schedule starts at 9 AM in the morning and runs until 9 AM the next morning.",
      "pos": [
        7047,
        7143
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It's important to note that the start and end times for a given schedule must both be contained on the same 24 hour schedule and cannot span multiple days.",
      "pos": [
        7144,
        7299
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you need to set up bandwidth templates that span multiple days, you will need to use multiple schedules (as shown in the example).",
      "pos": [
        7300,
        7433
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To create an all-day bandwidth template",
      "pos": [
        7441,
        7480
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Create a schedule that starts at 9 AM in the morning and runs until midnight.",
      "pos": [
        7485,
        7562
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Add another schedule.",
      "pos": [
        7567,
        7588
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Configure the second schedule to run from midnight until 9 AM in the morning.",
      "pos": [
        7589,
        7666
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Save the bandwidth template.",
      "pos": [
        7671,
        7699
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The composite schedule will then start at a time of your choosing and run all-day.",
      "pos": [
        7701,
        7783
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Questions and answers about bandwidth templates",
      "pos": [
        7788,
        7835
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Q<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        7837,
        7843
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "What happens to bandwidth controls when you are in between the schedules?",
      "pos": [
        7844,
        7917
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "(A schedule has ended and another one has not started yet.)",
      "pos": [
        7918,
        7977
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>A<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        7979,
        7985
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In such cases, no bandwidth controls will be employed.",
      "pos": [
        7986,
        8040
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This means that the device can use unlimited bandwidth when tiering data to the cloud.",
      "pos": [
        8041,
        8127
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Q<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        8129,
        8135
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Can you modify bandwidth templates on an offline device?",
      "pos": [
        8136,
        8192
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>A<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        8194,
        8200
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You will not be able to modify bandwidth templates on volumes containers if the corresponding device is offline.",
      "pos": [
        8201,
        8313
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Q<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        8315,
        8321
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Can you edit a bandwidth template associated with a volume container when the associated volumes are offline?",
      "pos": [
        8322,
        8431
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>A<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        8433,
        8439
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can modify a bandwidth template associated with a volume container whose volumes are offline.",
      "pos": [
        8440,
        8537
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Note that when volumes are offline, no data will be tiered from the device to the cloud.",
      "pos": [
        8538,
        8626
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Q<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        8628,
        8634
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Can you delete a default template?",
      "pos": [
        8635,
        8669
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>A<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        8671,
        8677
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Although you can delete a default template, it is not a good idea to do so.",
      "pos": [
        8678,
        8753
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The usage of a default template, including edited versions, is tracked.",
      "pos": [
        8754,
        8825
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The tracking data is analyzed and over the course of time, is used to improve the default template.",
      "pos": [
        8826,
        8925
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Q<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        8927,
        8933
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "How do you determine that your bandwidth templates need to be modified?",
      "pos": [
        8934,
        9005
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>A<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        9007,
        9013
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "One of the signs that you need to modify the bandwidth templates is when you start seeing the network slow down or choke multiple times in a day.",
      "pos": [
        9014,
        9159
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If this happens, monitor the storage and usage network by looking at the I/O Performance and Network Throughput charts.",
      "pos": [
        9160,
        9279
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "From the network throughput data, identify the time of day and the volume containers in which the network bottleneck occurs.",
      "pos": [
        9281,
        9405
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If this happens when data is being tiered to the cloud (get this information from I/O performance for all volume containers for device to cloud), then you will need to modify the bandwidth templates associated with your volume containers.",
      "pos": [
        9406,
        9644
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "After the modified templates are in use, you will need to monitor the network again for significant latencies.",
      "pos": [
        9646,
        9756
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If these still exist, then you will need to revisit your bandwidth templates.",
      "pos": [
        9757,
        9834
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Q<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        9836,
        9842
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "What happens if multiple volume containers on my device have schedules that overlap but different limits apply to each?",
      "pos": [
        9843,
        9962
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>A<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        9964,
        9970
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Let's assume that you have a device with 3 volume containers.",
      "pos": [
        9971,
        10032
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The schedules associated with these containers completely overlap.",
      "pos": [
        10033,
        10099
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For each of these containers, the bandwidth limits used are 5, 10, and 15 Mbps respectively.",
      "pos": [
        10100,
        10192
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When I/Os are occurring on all of these containers at the same time, the minimum of the 3 bandwidth limits may be applied: in this case, 5 Mbps as these outgoing I/O requests share the same queue.",
      "pos": [
        10193,
        10389
      ]
